ere the "incline" or table surface dictates the constraint).\n                    Wait, if it\'s an incline, the geometry is related. If it\'s a horizontal table with a pulley *at an angle* (e.g. a rope coming from a hanging block pulling at an angle), the constraint is strictly $v_M = v \\cos \\theta$.\n                    Let\'s calculate both and see if the difference is significant or if one leads to a "clean" answer.\n                    Given the phrasing, "rope makes a constant angle" suggests treating $\\theta$ as a parameter.\n                    If I assume $a_M = a \\cos \\theta$:\n                    Forces on $M$: $Mg - T = M (a \\cos \\theta)$.\n                    Forces on $m$: $T \\cos \\theta - f_k = m a$.\n                    Normal $N = mg - T \\sin \\theta$.\n                    $f_k = \\mu_k (mg - T \\sin \\theta)$.\n                    Substitute $T$:\n                    From $M$: $T = M(g - a \\cos \\theta)$.\n                    Into $m$: $M(g - a \\cos \\theta)\\cos \\theta - \\mu_k(mg - M(g - a \\cos \\theta)\\sin \\theta) = ma$.\n                    This seems like a plausible physical model where the rope is the constraint.\n                    \n                    What if the assumption is $a_M = a$?\n                    Forces on $M$: $Mg - T = Ma$.\n                    Forces on $m$: $T \\cos \\theta - \\mu_k(mg - T \\sin \\theta) = ma$.\n                    From $M$: $T = M(g-a)$.\n                    Into $m$: $M(g-a)\\cos \\theta - \\mu_k(mg - M(g-a)\\sin \\theta) = ma$.\n                    \n                    Which is more likely?\n                    The wording "hits the pulley" suggests the block covers the distance $d$ to the pulley.\n                    If the pulley is $d$ away, and the block reaches it, the geometry of the rope changes from angle $\\theta$ to angle 0 (or near 0) in a standard setup.\n                    The statement "rope makes a constant angle of $10.0^\\circ$" is a killer constraint. It implies the 