xpand term by term.\n$(ab+1)(bc+1) = ab^2c + ab + bc + 1$.\nMultiply by $(ca+1)$:\n$(ab^2c + ab + bc + 1)(ca+1) = (ab^2c)(ca) + ab^2c + (ab)(ca) + (bc)(ca) + 1(ca)$\nWait, $(ab^2c)(ca) = a^2b^2c^2$.\nThe terms are:\n1. $(ab^2c)(ca) = a^2b^2c^2 = (abc)^2$\n2. $ab^2c \\cdot 1 = ab^2c = abc \\cdot b$\n3. $ab \\cdot ca = a^2bc = abc \\cdot a$\n4. $bc \\cdot ca = abc^2 = abc \\cdot c$\n5. $1 \\cdot ca = ca$\n6. $ab \\cdot 1 = ab$\n7. $bc \\cdot 1 = bc$\n8. $1 \\cdot 1 = 1$\nWait, I missed something.\nLet\'s factor out $abc$ from the terms that are multiples of $abc$.\nThe expression is $(ab+1)(bc+1)(ca+1)$.\nModulo $abc$:\n$ab+1 \\equiv ab+1$.\n$bc+1 \\equiv bc+1$.\n$ca+1 \\equiv ca+1$.\nSo we need $(ab+1)(bc+1)(ca+1) \\equiv 0 \\pmod{abc}$.\nLet\'s expand the product again.\nProduct $= a^2b^2c^2 + a b^2 c + a^2 b c + a b c^2 + ab + bc + ca + 1$.\nWait, $ab \\cdot ca = a^2bc$. $bc \\cdot ca = ab c^2$. $ab \\cdot bc = ab^2c$.\nLet\'s group terms divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 1: $(ab)(bc)(ca) = (abc)^2$. This is divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 2: $(ab)(bc)(1) = ab^2c = b(abc)$. Divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 3: $(ab)(1)(ca) = a^2bc = a(abc)$. Divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 4: $(ab)(1)(1) = ab$. Not necessarily divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 5: $(1)(bc)(ca) = c(abc)$. Divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 6: $(1)(bc)(1) = bc$. Not necessarily divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 7: $(1)(1)(ca) = a(abc)$? No, $ca$. Not necessarily divisible by $abc$.\nTerm 8: $(1)(1)(1) = 1$. Not necessarily divisible by $abc$.\n\nSo the condition $(ab+1)(bc+1)(ca+1) \\equiv 0 \\pmod{abc}$ is equivalent to the sum of the "non-multiple" terms being divisible by $abc$.\nWait, that\'s not strictly true. It\'s the sum of *all* terms.\nLet $S = (ab+1)(bc+1)(ca+1)$.\n$S = a^2b^2c^2 + a b^2 c + a^2 b c + a b c^2 + ab + bc + ca + 1$.\n$S = (abc)^2 + abc(b + c + a) + ab + bc + ca + 1$.\n$S = abc(abc + a + b + c) + (ab + bc + ca + 1)$.\nFor $abc$ to divide $S$, it must divide the remaining term $(ab + bc + ca + 1)$.\nSo the condition is equivalent 