n $n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod M$ is NOT what is required.\nLet\'s be precise.\n$n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod 7$\n$n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod{11}$\n$n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod{13}$\nThis is equivalent to $n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod{7 \\times 11 \\times 13}$ by Chinese Remainder Theorem ONLY if $k$ is the same integer.\nWait. $n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod 7$ means $n^2 = 7a + k$.\n$n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod{11}$ means $n^2 = 11b + k$.\n$n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod{13}$ means $n^2 = 13c + k$.\nThis implies $n^2 - k$ is divisible by 7, 11, and 13.\nSo $n^2 \\equiv k \\pmod{1001}$.\nHere $k$ is the specific integer remainder value.\nBut wait. The problem statement says "$n^2$ has the same remainder when divided by 7, 11, and 13".\nLet $r_7 = n^2 \\pmod 7$. Let $r_{11} = n^2 \\pmod{11}$. Let $r_{13} = n^2 \\pmod{13}$.\nThe condition is $r_7 = r_{11} = r_{13}$. Let\'s call this common value $x$.\nSince $r_7 \\in \\{0, 1, ..., 6\\}$, $r_{11} \\in \\{0, 1, ..., 10\\}$, and $r_{13} \\in \\{0, 1, ..., 12\\}$, the common value $x$ must be in $\\{0, 1, ..., 6\\}$.\nAlso $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod 7$, $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{11}$, $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{13}$.\nThis implies $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{\\text{lcm}(7, 11, 13)}$.\nSince 7, 11, 13 are coprime, $\\text{lcm}(7, 11, 13) = 1001$.\nSo the condition is equivalent to: $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{1001}$ for some $x \\in \\{0, 1, ..., 6\\}$ such that $x$ is a quadratic residue mod 7, 11, and 13. Actually, if $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{1001}$, then $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod 7$ automatically. But the condition "$n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{1001}$" means $n^2 = m \\cdot 1001 + x$.\nThen $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod 7$, $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{11}$, $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{13}$.\nSo the remainders are all $x$.\nSo the condition simplifies to: $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{1001}$ where $0 \\le x \\le 6$.\nWait, is it required that $x$ is a quadratic residue mod 1001?\nYes, if $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod{1001}$, then $n^2 - x = 1001k$.\nThis implies $n^2 \\equiv x \\pmod 7$, so $x$ must be a quadratic residue modulo 7.\nIt implies $n^2 \\equiv