        Check $9(9^{2010} - 1) \\equiv 0 \\pmod{17}$.\n        $9 \\not\\equiv 0$.\n        Need $9^{2010} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{17}$.\n        Order of 9 modulo 17?\n        $9 = 3^2$.\n        $9^{16} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{17}$ (FLT).\n        Actually, $9^2 = 81 = 4 \\times 17 + 13 \\equiv 13 \\equiv -4$.\n        $9^4 \\equiv (-4)^2 = 16 \\equiv -1$.\n        So $9^8 \\equiv 1 \\pmod{17}$.\n        The order is 8.\n        We need to check if 2010 is divisible by 8.\n        $2010 / 2 = 1005$. Odd.\n        So $2010$ is not divisible by 8.\n        Thus $9^{2010} \\equiv 9^{2010 \\pmod 8} \\pmod{17}$.\n        $2010 = 2000 + 10$.\n        $2000 \\equiv 0 \\pmod 8$ (since $1000$ div by 8).\n        $10 \\equiv 2 \\pmod 8$.\n        So $9^{2010} \\equiv 9^2 \\pmod{17}$.\n        $9^2 = 81 = 17 \\times 4 + 13 \\equiv 13 \\equiv -4 \\pmod{17}$.\n        So $9^{2010} - 1 \\equiv -4 - 1 = -5 \\not\\equiv 0 \\pmod{17}$.\n        So $9^{2010} - 1$ is not divisible by 17.\n        What about the factor 9 in $S$? $9 \\equiv 9 \\not\\equiv 0$.\n        What about the denominator 8? $8$ is coprime to 17.\n        So $S$ is *not* divisible by 17.\n\n    *   **Let me double check the previous primes.**\n        It\'s easy to make a calculation error.\n\n        Check $p=2$:\n        $S = 9 + 9^2 + \\dots + 9^{2010}$.\n        Sum of 2010 odd numbers. Even number of terms. Even sum.\n        Correct.\n\n        Check $p=3$:\n        $S = 9 + \\dots$ multiple of 9. Correct.\n\n        Check $p=5$:\n        $9 \\equiv -1 \\pmod 5$.\n        $\\sum_{k=1}^{2010} (-1)^k$.\n        Since 2010 is even, pairs cancel. Sum = 0. Correct.\n\n        Check $p=7$:\n        $S = \\frac{9(9^{2010}-1)}{8}$.\n        Need $9^{2010} \\equiv 1 \\pmod 7$.\n        $9 \\equiv 2 \\pmod 7$.\n        Order of 2 mod 7 is 3 ($2^1=2, 2^2=4, 2^3=1$). Wait, Fermat says $2^6 \\equiv 1$.\n        Let\'s check order.\n        $2^1=2, 2^2=4, 2^3=8 \\equiv 1$.\n        Order is 3.\n        We need $2010$ divisible by 3.\n        Sum of digits of 2010 is $2+0+1+0=3$. Divisible by 3.\n        So $2^{2010} = (2^3)^{670} \\equiv 1 \\pmod 7$.\n        Wait, I used order 6 previously (Fermat\'s Little Theorem). That\'s also valid.\n        If exponent is multiple of order, it is 1.\n        If exponent is multiple of $p-1$, it is 1.\n        Multiples of 3 are a subset of multiples of 6.\n        Since $2010$ is div by 3, $2^{2010} \\equiv 1 \\pmod 7$.\n        So $S \\equiv 0 \\pmod 7$. Correct.\n\n        Check $p=11$:\n        $9 \\equiv -2 \\pmod{11}$.\n        Need $(-2)^{2010} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{11}$.\n        $(-2)^{2010} = 2^{2010}$.\n        FLT: $2^{10} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{11}$.\n        Does 10 divide 2010? Yes.\n        So $2^{2010} \\equiv 1$.\n        So $S \\equiv 0 \\pmod{11}$. Correct.\n\n        Check $p=13$:\n        $9 \\pmod{13}$.\n        $9^{2010} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{13}$.\n        $9 = 3^2$.\n        FLT: $3^{12} \\equiv 1$.\n        Order of 9 modulo 13?\n        $9^1 = 9$.\n        $9^2 = 81 = 6 \\cdot 13 + 3$.\n        $9^3 = 9 \\cdot 3 = 27 = 1$.\n        Order of 9 is 3.\n        Need 3 to divide 2010.\n        $2010$ is divisible by 3.\n        So $9^{2010} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{13}$.\n        So $S \\equiv 0 \\pmod{13}$. Correct.\n\n        Check $p=17$:\n        $S = \\frac{9(9^{2010}-1)}{8}$.\n        Check $9^{2010} \\equiv 1 \\pmod{17}$.\n        Order of 9 mod 17?\n        $9 = 3^2$.\n        $3^1=3, 3^2=9, 3^3=27=10$.\n        $9^2 = 81 = 4 \\cdot 17 + 13 \\equiv -4$.\n        $9^4 \\equiv 16 \\equiv -1$.\n        $9^8 \\equiv 1$.\n        Order is 8.\n        Does 8 divide 2010?\n        $2010 / 2 = 1005$ (odd). No.\n        So $9^{2010} \\not\\equiv 1 \\pmod{17}$.\n        So $S$ is not divisible by 17.\n\n        **Hold on.** Is there a prime smaller than 17 that I missed?\n        Primes: 2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13, 17.\n        I checked all.\n        2, 3, 5, 7, 11, 13 are divisors.\n        17 is not.\n\n        Let me re-verify the "Does 17 divide S" part.\n      