e sum to 0 with $a_k \\le 0$, then $a_k=0$.\n    So for a solution to exist with $a_k \\neq 0$, we need positive endpoints.\n    Actually, if $\\max(|a_1|, |a_n|) = 1$, let\'s assume w.l.o.g. that the "positive" part is near the endpoints to allow the "negative" dip in the middle to be large.\n    If $a_1, a_n > 0$, then $a_k$ can be negative.\n    Let\'s test $n=3$.\n    $a_1, a_2, a_3$.\n    $2a_2 \\le a_1 + a_3$.\n    $a_1 + a_2 + a_3 = 0$.\n    We want to bound $|a_2|$.\n    From $a_1 + a_3 = -a_2$.\n    Condition: $2a_2 \\le -a_2 \\implies 3a_2 \\le 0 \\implies a_2 \\le 0$.\n    So $a_2$ is negative.\n    Also $a_1 + a_3 = -a_2 \\ge 0$.\n    So $a_1, a_3$ must sum to a positive number.\n    Also convexity holds.\n    Let\'s check the constraint $\\lambda(3)$.\n    We need $|a_2| \\le \\lambda(3) \\max(|a_1|, |a_3|)$.\n    Let $|a_1|=1, |a_3|=0$ (if possible). Then $a_1=1, a_3=0$.\n    $a_2 = -(1+0)/1 = -1$.\n    Is convexity satisfied? $2(-1) \\le 1 + 0 \\implies -2 \\le 1$. Yes.\n    So $|a_2| = 1$. Max endpoint magnitude is 1. So ratio is 1.\n    Is it possible to get higher?\n    We have $a_2 = -(a_1 + a_3)$.\n    We want to maximize $|a_2| / \\max(|a_1|, |a_3|)$ given $2a_2 \\le a_1+a_3$ and $\\sum a_i = 0$.\n    Substitute $\\sum=0$: $2(-a_1-a_3) \\le a_1 + a_3 \\implies -2(a_1+a_3) \\le a_1+a_3 \\implies -3(a_1+a_3) \\le 0 \\implies a_1+a_3 \\ge 0$.\n    We want to maximize $- (a_1+a_3)$ subject to $|a_1|, |a_3| \\le 1$ and $a_1+a_3 \\ge 0$.\n    To maximize $-(a_1+a_3)$, we need to minimize $a_1+a_3$.\n    But $a_1+a_3 \\ge 0$. The minimum is 0. If sum is 0, $a_2=0$, ratio 0.\n    Wait, I substituted $\\sum=0$ into the inequality.\n    The problem asks for a bound for *all* sequences.\n    The ratio is $|a_k| / M$. We want to find the supremum of this ratio.\n    Let\'s look at $a_2$. $a_2 = -(a_1+a_3)$.\n    $a_2$ must be $\\le 0$ derived above. So $|a_2| = a_1+a_3$.\n    We want to maximize $a_1+a_3$ given $\\max(|a_1|, |a_3|)=1$ and $a_1+a_3 \\ge 0$.\